    {
      "name": "complexity_definitions",
      "displayName": "Complexity Definitions",
      "layout": [
        {
          "widget": {
            "name": "title",
            "multilineTextboxSpec": {
              "lines": [
                "# Complexity Definitions\n",
                "## Bladespector Assessment Rules\n",
                "\n",
                "Bladespector (Lakebridge's analyzer) categorizes source files into LOW / MEDIUM / HIGH complexity based on technology-specific heuristics. These are **analytic transpilability** indicators \u2014 they measure migration effort, NOT whether the LLM transpiler (Switch) can handle them."
              ]
            }
          },
          "position": {
            "x": 0,
            "y": 0,
            "width": 12,
            "height": 3
          }
        },
        {
          "widget": {
            "name": "tsql_section",
            "multilineTextboxSpec": {
              "lines": [
                "## T-SQL (MS SQL Server)\n",
                "\n",
                "Complexity is derived from the **file purpose** (naming convention):\n",
                "\n",
                "| Complexity | Rule | Examples |\n",
                "|---|---|---|\n",
                "| **HIGH** | Stored procedures (`sp_`), upsert patterns | `sp_load_customer_metrics.sql`, `sp_upsert_inventory.sql` |\n",
                "| **MEDIUM** | ETL patterns: extract, incremental load | `incremental_extract.sql` |\n",
                "| **LOW** | Simple DDL, schema definitions, basic queries | `schema_sales.sql` |\n",
                "\n",
                "Transpiler: `sqlglot` (deterministic, no LLM). All T-SQL files are transpilable."
              ]
            }
          },
          "position": {
            "x": 0,
            "y": 3,
            "width": 12,
            "height": 5
          }
        },
        {
          "widget": {
            "name": "ssis_section",
            "multilineTextboxSpec": {
              "lines": [
                "## SSIS Packages\n",
                "\n",
